# properties and attributes 
  1) in html source code, one can define "attributes" of an html element
     once the browser parses the source code, a corresponding DOM node object will be created
     (as the node is an object, it has many "properties")

    ex. 
        <input type="text" value="Name:">    <== an html element which has 2 attributes

        an HTMLInputElement node object will be created, the node object has dozens of properties
        (ex. accept, attributes, align, baseURL, childNodes, classList, className, etc.)

  2) for a given DOM node object,
     properties: properties of a DOM node object, which has an attributes property
     attributes: elements of that attributes property of the DOM node object

  3) when a DOM node object is created for a given html element, many of its properties relate to attributes with
     the same or similar names

     ex.
         <input id="the-input" type="text" value="Name:">

         the corresponding DOM node object have id, type, and value properties
         a) the id property is a reflected property for the id attribute (pure: doesn't modify/limit the value)
            i.e. getting the property reads the attribute value, setting the property writes the attribute value
         b) the type property is a reflected property for the type attribute (not pure: limited to known values)
            i.e. having the valid types of an input
                 if you had <input type="foo">, then
                 theInput.getAttribute("type") gives you "foo" but theInput.type gives you "text"
         c) the value property doesn't reflect the value attribute, instead it is the current value of the input
            i.e. when the user changes the value of the input box, the value property reflects this change
                 ex.
                   if the user inputs "John" into the input box, then
                   theInput.value // returns "John"
                   whereas
                   theInput.getAttribute('value') // returns "Name:"

                   the value property reflects the current text-content inside the input box, whereas
                   the value attribute contains initial text-content of value attribute from HTML source code

# html table
  <table style="width:100%">
    <tr>
      <th>TableHeader1</th>
      <th>TableHeader2</th> 
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>TableData1</td>
      <td>TableData2</td> 
    </tr>
  </table>

# html image: <img src="url" alt="some_text" style="width:width;height:height;">
  ex.
    <img id="image-2" src="http://example.com" style="width: 100%; height: 23.3333vh;">

